  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2642499263" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2642499263" />
    <a title="Steve R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r"><img alt="Steve R" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1550608435p2/51602729.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2642499263?book_show_action=true">Jan 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve R" href="/user/show/51602729-steve-r">Steve R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2642499263" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer794686729112167846">Having reread this novel, I am impressed by how one can take it as a representation of several different genres. The difficulty in deciding which one it is to the greatest degree is somewhat of a drawback. Firstly, it is a cautionary tale of the potential dangers of technological developments. Then, it is a mystery novel. Then, it is a love story. Then, it is a moral homily. Finally, and I believe most frequently, it is an action adventure.<br/><br/>The conception of the Grail Brotherhood&apos;s &apos;immortality m</span>
  <span id="freeText794686729112167846" style="display:none">Having reread this novel, I am impressed by how one can take it as a representation of several different genres. The difficulty in deciding which one it is to the greatest degree is somewhat of a drawback. Firstly, it is a cautionary tale of the potential dangers of technological developments. Then, it is a mystery novel. Then, it is a love story. Then, it is a moral homily. Finally, and I believe most frequently, it is an action adventure.<br /><br />The conception of the Grail Brotherhood's 'immortality machines' as they are aptly termed by Orlando, through which they attempt to establish VR simulations within which to live as Gods for all eternity, is truly an impressive one. The many manifestations these simulations take - an insect world, the England of the post-Martian attack from Wells' <i>War of the Worlds</i>, an Egyptian desert, the strange, strange kitchen, a prehistoric Neanderthal/Ice age world, Coleridge's Xanadu, Venice of the Renaissance, even the final colorless, featureless simulation <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[in which most of the members of Renie's infiltrating group find themselves <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>- are highly detailed and interesting conceptions. However, the underlying issue remains as to whether or not they are actually serving any legitimate purpose. Are they simply expensive playthings with no redeeming value and, in addition, with an insidious effect on those trapped in them? Is this really what we want from our computers and their associated technological possibilities: a complete escape from reality?<br /><br />Williams delights in keeping his readers guessing. His clues are suitably cryptic (seek the home of the wanderer and release the weaver, go to the black mountain, follow the darkness), and very rarely lead to anything tangible in less than at least a hundred pages. Yet even more so, the overwhelming issue of what has caused the children like Stephen, Renie's brother, to fall into seemingly irreversible comas, hovers over all the actions of both the good guys and the bad guys throughout the book spoiler&gt;with no real resolution reached. The purpose and progress of the Nemesis program is presented, but raises many more questions than it provides answers. The identity and motive of 'The Other', as well as his 'name that tune' query are puzzling, as is the makeup and background of 'The Circle' who supposedly oppose the Brotherhood. Why Paul continually meets the mysterious 'bird lady' is another issue to ponder, and the actual 'life' situation of Emily 22813 and Gally is unclear: they are supposedly not 'puppets', but does this mean they have real people personas in RL? Finally, the identity of the mole within the group is a frustrating issue, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[one that when it was resolved I had to realize that I'd been completely fooled! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />The developing relationship Between Renie and !Xabbu is realized, at least on the part of the former, to resemble love. Still, what the exact form this emotion means to her is as yet undecided. Certainly, her feelings for Stephen, Paul's for Gally, Jeremiah's for the memory of Susan, Quan Li's for her granddaughter and even Long Joseph's for his son (though you could argue that his love for wine is really more pronounced) all betoken Williams' recognition that this interpersonal feeling is a strong contradiction to the selfish insensitivity of the Brotherhood to all human life except their own.<br /><br />The character of !Xabbu, bizarrely yet imaginatively represented throughout the majority of the novel in the simulated body of a baboon, once again provides the moral focus of the story: his stories, epigrams, dances, and general ruminative persona all make for a higher plane of consciousness that helps all those of his party to see through the confusion of their ever changing and challenging situations to what is most important: in the last novel, it was 'to hear the sun'; in this work, it is 'to see with one's heart'. Further, he states that has had 'to see again with the eyes that were given to me, to see with the heart of my people, something I have not done since we have been in this place, in this mirage.' <br /><br />Felix Jongleur's nigh-on two hundred year old life is working to make such a vision unattainable. Dread's atavistic pleasure in the act of killing represents a truly repugnant antithesis to !Xabbu's fundamental humanity. The new characters of Olga Perfosky, Decatur Ramsay and Calliope Skouros are welcome additions to the ongoing story. Even Dread's minion Dulcie provides a different perspective. The engaging back story of Martine is also a welcome interlude.<br /><br />But characterization falls short of the eternal thrust of narrative tension in Williams' approach (just as technological exposition largely precludes moral analysis): the book is almost a non-ending series of daring-do exploits and highly taut dramatic moments of peril. The crashing dragonfly plane, the attack by the giant praying mantis, the discovery of Sellars' underground lair by ChoCho, Orlando and Fredericks defending themselves against vicious salad tongs (!), the attack by the pirates in their gravy boat on the icebox in the kitchen simulation, Christobel's meeting General Yacoubian at her father's offices, the many encounters of Paul with Finney and Mudd (aka Mullet and Finch and/or Undine Parker and her husband), the nefarious Scarecrow and Lion in the Emerald City simulation, the perilous darkness of The Place of the Lost in Aerodromia, and the fight for the lighter with Dread: these are all virtually cinematic treasures of description and action.<br /><br />It is this which makes this work a four- rather than a five-star rating for me. I would much have preferred less excitement and more thought. As well, William's pattern of flipping from character to character or group to group from chapter to chapter (and even sometimes within chapters) makes for a disconcerting sense of progress. Paul does something, then you flip to Christobel, then to Renie and !Xabbu, then to Dread, then to Martine and her group, then to Felix, then to Dulcie, then to Olga, then to Calliope, then to Ramsay, then back to Renie and !Xabbu, by which time you have to do quite a bit of recalibrating to remember when and where you last encountered this character or group. It's as if I was reading sixty short stories more than a a six hundred page novel.<br /><br />Nevertheless, it does deserve a solid four star rating, if only for the imaginative construction of such a complex web of mysteries, characters, actions and moral issues.</span>
  <a data-text-id="794686729112167846" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


