<div id="review_307119759" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/307119759" />
    <a title="Phil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2935621-phil"><img alt="Phil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1318005507p2/2935621.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/307119759?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phil" href="/user/show/2935621-phil">Phil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer307119759" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17840265640837642970">These books take me forever to read in between the hustle and bustle of life. I often read lots of online material and currently working my way through the Sandman graphic novel so I have plenty of distractions to keep from completing a book if it isn&apos;t grabbing me. Although I can&apos;t say that I didn&apos;t enjoy following through with characters&apos; journey through all the virtual worlds, it just didn&apos;t seem to grab me. There was never a moment where I simply couldn&apos;t put it down which means I was never </span>
  <span id="freeText17840265640837642970" style="display:none">These books take me forever to read in between the hustle and bustle of life. I often read lots of online material and currently working my way through the Sandman graphic novel so I have plenty of distractions to keep from completing a book if it isn't grabbing me. Although I can't say that I didn't enjoy following through with characters' journey through all the virtual worlds, it just didn't seem to grab me. There was never a moment where I simply couldn't put it down which means I was never rushing to read it. Hence why the three stars.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Tad Williams is great writer even if he is a little long winded which is probably why I haven't simply bailed from the series. I've pulled some great quotes I highlighted while going through the book and attached them to my status updates if your interested. Although Renie's dad is still a dolt, we really got to see Renie evolve from the more mild mannered lady of the first book. There's a few occasions where she snaps and shows a much harsher side. Although there has been some incredible experiences in these worlds and further insights into the characters, the plot is moving very slowly toward the group finally coming to grips with their surroundings and feeling a small glint of hope in possibly getting out of Otherland alive.<br /><br />Dread is a nasty piece of work. Can't wait to see the consequences of his 'endearing' needs catch up with him. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Anyway, I'm going to keep plodding my way through this series. Although the next book in the series is only about 650 pages or so, I noticed the last one is pushing on a 1000! It'll be the end the year before I get through these!<br /><br />I'm also finding that one of the great things about eBooks is having all the annotations and highlights digitized, but it did take me a while to figure out how extract all this information from both a Kobo and an iPad. Definitely not something they have made easy and the jury is still out whether it is worth the effort. I need to streamline how I make that work. Can't wait for a decent app utility to automate the process. I'm also looking into using Sigil to append my annotations directly into an ePub book. Not something I would usually spend the time doing, but as instructor I'm thinking this could be a great addition for students annotating their textbooks or my notes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17840265640837642970" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


